messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full request path:
- /admin/media/{media}

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- all methods: false

Per-method acceptability for the path /admin/media/{media}:
- HEAD: true
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation / reasoning
- The routes file (routes/admin.php) registers a resource route:
  - Route::resource('media', MediaLibraryController::class)->only(['index', 'show', 'create', 'store', 'destroy']);
  - That creates the standard resource URIs for "media". The show and destroy routes are the ones with a path parameter: /media/{media}.
- The controller redirects using route('admin.media.index'), which indicates these admin routes are loaded with the "admin" prefix / admin route-name prefix in the application's route group. Therefore the full path is /admin/media/{media}.
- Mapping of resource actions to HTTP verbs for the {media} path:
  - show -> GET /admin/media/{media}  (so GET is acceptable)
  - destroy -> DELETE /admin/media/{media} (so DELETE is acceptable)
- HEAD is marked true because a GET route (show) exists for the same URI; Laravel will respond to HEAD requests for routes that have GET handlers (HEAD is implied for GET). Other methods (POST, PUT, PATCH, TRACE, OPTIONS) are not defined by the resource routes, so they are not acceptable for this specific endpoint.
- all methods is false because the route is not defined with Route::any or equivalent that would allow every HTTP method.
- Note: the controller method signatures use Media $medium (variable named $medium) while the resource parameter is {media}; this name mismatch can affect implicit route-model binding unless custom binding is configured or the parameter name is adjusted. That does not change the registered paths and methods derived from the routes file.
